║   6. RECOMMENDATIONS                                         ║
╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

Based on diagnostic analysis:

1. NEGATIVE EIGENVALUES:
   Problem: Hessian is not positive definite
   Likely cause: Model overparameterization
   → Some parameters are not well-identified
   → Flat likelihood surface in some directions

2. NaN STANDARD ERRORS:
   9 / 18 parameters have undefined SEs
   Affected: β₀ (baseline), γ (population), β_2016, β_2017, β_2018, ...
   → These parameters cannot be reliably estimated

3. PARAMETERS WITH LARGE STANDARD ERRORS (SE > 10):
   δ (poverty): SE = 33.15
   β_2023: SE = 14.51
   → High uncertainty, poorly identified

RECOMMENDED ACTIONS:
-------------------

Option A: SIMPLIFY TEMPORAL STRUCTURE
  • Replace 9 year fixed effects with linear trend
  • Reduces parameters from 18 → 10
  • Previous test: LL = -113,113 (much worse)
  • But may improve identifiability

Option B: DROP POVERTY
  • Poverty effect has huge SE (33.15) and is non-significant
  • May be collinear with log(pop) despite r = -0.48
  • Test: Fit model without delta parameter
  • Reduces parameters from 18 → 17

Option C: COMBINE YEAR EFFECTS
  • Group years into periods (e.g., 2015-2017, 2018-2020, 2021-2024)
  • Reduces 9 year effects → 2-3 period effects
  • Reduces parameters from 18 → 11-12

Option D: SIMPLIFY MARKS
  • Student and labor both suppress triggering
  • Could combine into single "organized" indicator
  • Reduces parameters from 18 → 17

Option E: USE BOOTSTRAP (NO SIMPLIFICATION)
  • Accept that Hessian-based SEs don't work
  • Use bootstrap resampling for inference
  • Computationally expensive but robust
  • Recommended if you want to keep full model

PRIORITY RECOMMENDATION:
  1. Try Option B (drop poverty) - smallest change, may fix issue
  2. If still problematic, try Option C (combine year effects)
  3. If inference still needed, use Option E (bootstrap)

